properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm, with localized higher amounts possible in some areas. Maximum wind gusts: easterly 80 km/h. Locations: eastern Newfoundland. Time span: tonight. Remarks: Snow and strong easterly winds will give poor visibility in blowing snow. Visibility will improve as the snow changes to rain or drizzle before morning. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2020-01-20T18:10:29-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 25 cm is expected. A slow moving Pacific frontal system will continue to give snow over the Williston region and Pine Pass this morning. 15 to 25 cm of snow has accumulated form the current storm and another 5 cm is possible this morning The snow will finally ease this afternoon. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls tonight. A strong snow squall off Southern Lake Huron extends from near Kettle Point across Wyoming towards the Bothwell area. This snow squall is expected to persist through the night before weakening to a few flurries by early Monday morning. Snowfall amounts up to 15 cm will be possible tonight with this snow squall. In addition, sudden near zero visibility from bursts of heavy snow and blowing snow is expected. Dangerous winter driving conditions are likely tonight along Highway 402. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Under clear skies, extreme wind chills near minus 40 are expected in eastern Saskatchewan and western Manitoba tonight. These extreme wind chill values will moderate Monday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
